rarely subject to judicial penalties, and society tended to blame self-inflicted death on insanity rather than on the devil. From Sin to Insanity shows that early modern Europe witnessed nothing less than the birth of modern suicide: increasing in frequency, self-inflicted death became decriminalized, secularized, and medicalized, viewed as a regrettable but not shameful result of reversals in fortune or physical or mental infirmity. The ten chapters focus on suicide cases and attitudes toward self-murder from the fifteenth to the early nineteenth centuries in geographical settings as diverse as Scandinavia and Hungary, France and Germany, England and Switzerland, Spain and the Netherlands.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSuicidexHistory. 0aSuicide. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aAndrew, Donna T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBosman, Machiel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyden, James M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickenson, Elizabeth G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansson, Arne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoslofsky, Craig M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLederer, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLind, Vera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerrick, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeaver, Paul S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatt, Jeffrey R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatt, Jeffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08